Document: Debugger Panel
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/debugger_panel.rst
Summary: This section describes how to use the Visual Profiler in Godot to identify rendering bottlenecks on the CPU and GPU.

The Visual Profiler helps monitor rendering performance by showing what takes the most time on the CPU and GPU per frame, aiding in the tracking of rendering bottlenecks.

Warning: The Visual Profiler measures only CPU time for rendering tasks like draw calls. It does not include CPU time for scripting or physics. Use the standard Profiler tab for non-rendering CPU tasks.

To use the Visual Profiler:
1. Run your project.
2. Navigate to the **Visual Profiler** tab in the Debugger's bottom panel.
3. Click **Start**.

Tip: You can enable **Autostart** to automatically begin profiling when the project runs next. The state of the **Autostart** checkbox is not saved between editor sessions.

While the profiler runs, categories and results will appear. CPU framegraphs are shown on the left, and GPU framegraphs on the right.

Click **Stop** to freeze the results. The results remain visible after stopping the project but not after closing the editor.

You can click on result categories on the left to highlight them in the CPU and GPU graphs on the right. Clicking on the graph allows you to move a cursor to a specific frame number and highlight the corresponding data type in the result categories.

Results can be displayed as time in milliseconds per frame or as a percentage of the target frametime (currently 16.67 milliseconds, or 60 FPS).

If framerate spikes occur, they can affect graph scaling. Disable **Fit to Frame** to zoom the graph onto the 60 FPS+ portion.

Note: Visual Profiler results can vary significantly based on viewport resolution, which is determined by window size when using the `disabled` or `canvas_items` stretch modes. Ensure consistent viewport sizes when comparing results across different runs.

The Visual Profiler supports all rendering methods (Forward+, Mobile, Compatibility), but reported categories differ based on the rendering method and enabled graphics features. For example, in Forward+ with a 2D scene and shadow-casting lights, specific categories will appear.

In a Forward+ 3D scene with shadow-casting lights and various effects, different categories will be enabled.

In the 3D example, categories with "(Parallel)" appended indicate multiple tasks running concurrently on the GPU. Disabling only one feature in such cases may not yield significant performance improvements as other tasks still run sequentially.

Note: The Visual Profiler is not supported on macOS when using the Compatibility renderer due to platform limitations.
---CHUNK---
Document: Debugger Panel
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/debugger_panel.rst
Summary: Describes the Network Profiler section of the Debugger panel, including its node list, counters, and bandwidth meter.
The Network Profiler contains a list of all the nodes that communicate over the multiplayer API and, for each one, some counters on the amount of incoming and outgoing network interactions. It also features a bandwidth meter that displays the total bandwidth usage at any given moment. Note: The bandwidth meter does not take the high-level multiplayer API's own compression system into account. This means that changing the compression algorithm used will not change the metrics reported by the bandwidth meter.
---CHUNK---
Document: Debugger Panel
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/debugger_panel.rst
Summary: This section describes the performance monitors available in the Godot debugger.
The monitors are graphs of several aspects of the game while it's running such as FPS, memory usage, how many nodes are in a scene and more. All monitors keep track of stats automatically, so even if one monitor isn't open while the game is running, you can open it later and see how the values changed.
See also: In addition to the default performance monitors, you can also create custom performance monitors to track arbitrary values in your project.
---CHUNK---
Document: Debugger Panel
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/debugger_panel.rst
Summary: This section describes the Video RAM tab in the Godot debugger, detailing its purpose and the information it displays.
The Video RAM tab shows the video RAM usage of the game while it is running. It provides a list of every resource using video RAM by resource path, the type of resource it is, what format it is in, and how much Video RAM that resource is using. There is also a total video RAM usage number at the top right of the panel.
---CHUNK---
Document: Debugger Panel
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/debugger_panel.rst
Summary: Describes the 'Misc' tab in the Godot debugger, which helps identify control nodes at runtime.

Misc
The Misc tab contains tools to identify the control nodes you are clicking at runtime.
- Clicked Control tells you where the clicked node is in the scene tree.
- Clicked Control Type tells you the type of the node you clicked is.